      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":339,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Keep this genuinely easy — conversational pace throughout. If you find yourself breathing hard, slow down. This run builds aerobic base and aids recovery from the weekend long run.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with 5 minutes of easy walking or very light jogging to ease into the effort.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5 minutes of easy walking and light dynamic stretching — calves, hip flexors, hamstrings.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundation run for the week. Easy runs do more physiological work than they feel like they do — they build mitochondrial density, improve fat oxidation, and support recovery. The goal is to arrive at Tuesday feeling better than when you started, not depleted. Resist any urge to push the pace here.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Lactate Threshold Tempo Run\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":52,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":256,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease into this gradually. The warmup is not optional — your threshold pace will feel much harder without it. Aim for the slower end of easy pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":25,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":256,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"This is comfortably hard — you should be able to speak in short phrases but not hold a conversation. 4:16/km is your threshold pace. Stay controlled and even-effort throughout. Do not start too fast.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Bring the effort down gradually. The cooldown helps clear lactate and begins the recovery process. Do not skip this.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy jog at 5:07–5:39/km before beginning the tempo portion. Include a few light strides in the final minute if your legs feel sluggish.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3 km easy jog at easy pace, followed by 5 minutes of walking and static stretching focusing on calves, quads, and hip flexors.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Threshold running is the single most important quality for marathon performance. It raises your lactate threshold — the pace you can sustain before fatigue accelerates — which directly translates to a faster marathon. At 4:16/km, this should feel like a 7/10 effort: controlled discomfort, not suffering. If it feels easy, trust the pace and resist speeding up. If it feels impossible, back off slightly and check in with how the week's load has felt overall.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":58,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":237,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"A thorough warmup is essential before interval work. Finish with 4–6 strides at a comfortably quick pace to prime your neuromuscular system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":237,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 1 km at 3:57/km with 90-second standing or very slow jog recovery between each rep. This pace should feel hard — around 9/10 — but controlled. Focus on smooth, relaxed form even when it gets tough. Do not sprint the first rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":400,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"90 seconds to 2 minutes of very easy jogging or walking between each kilometer rep. This recovery is deliberate — it allows partial restoration so the next rep can be run at full quality.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Bring the heart rate down gradually with an easy jog. Your body is doing significant repair work in the hours after this session — honor that.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy jog, finishing with 4–6 x 20-second strides with full recovery between each. This primes your legs for the intensity ahead.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2–3 km easy jog followed by walking and thorough stretching. Pay particular attention to hip flexors and calves after interval work.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2Max intervals are the sharpest tool in the marathon training kit. They raise your aerobic ceiling — the maximum rate at which your body can use oxygen — which ultimately allows your threshold and marathon paces to feel more sustainable. Five 1 km reps at 3:57/km is a meaningful but manageable dose for your current fitness. The key is consistency across all five reps: if rep 1 and rep 5 feel dramatically different, you started too fast. Aim for even splits or a very slight negative split across the set.\",\"perceived_effort\":9},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":26,\"target_duration_minutes\":147,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":339,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":147,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run the full distance at easy pace — 5:07 to 5:39/km. The long run is about time on feet and aerobic adaptation, not pace. If you feel good in the final third, you may drift toward the faster end of easy, but do not push into marathon pace territory today. Stay patient.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with 5–10 minutes of easy walking before settling into your running pace. Your body needs time to warm up, especially on a Sunday morning.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5–10 minutes of walking, then spend 10–15 minutes on full-body stretching. Prioritize nutrition and hydration within 30–45 minutes of finishing — this is when your muscles are most receptive to glycogen replenishment.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the cornerstone of marathon preparation. At 26 km, you are already running a distance that builds significant aerobic infrastructure — increased capillary density, improved fat utilization, and enhanced muscular endurance. The pace here is deliberately easy because the adaptation comes from duration, not intensity. Running this too fast is one of the most common marathon training mistakes — it compromises recovery and reduces the quality of your quality sessions later in the week. Trust the process: easy long runs make fast marathons.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
